Clocks.

A clock tells the player the current time. Stand on a clock, press the interact key, and it speaks a lead-in you chose followed by the time of day. It ticks quietly the whole time it's there, so the player can find it by ear. A clock is essentially a sign that ends with the live time instead of fixed words — useful for timed challenges, for atmosphere, or simply for letting the player check the hour.

A clock is built in two variants, chosen from the build mode list: a single clock (one tile) and a ranged clock (a rectangular area the player can read from anywhere inside).

How a clock works.

A clock with a sound theme plays a quiet ticking loop across its area for as long as it exists, so the player can hear where it is — unlike a sign, whose ambient loop is optional, a clock always ticks. While the player is inside it and presses the interact key, the clock plays a press cue and speaks its text immediately followed by the current time. If the clock is destroyable, bombs and projectiles can smash it; it plays a break sound and is gone.

Clock fields.

The clock form takes the following:

Coordinates. A single clock takes an x and y (and z on 3d maps); a ranged clock takes a minimum and maximum x and y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), chosen with the ranged option in the build mode list.

Text. The lead-in spoken just before the time, which defaults to "The time is ". The current time is appended to it automatically when the clock is read.

Clock sound (a folder name from the clock sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the ticking loop, a press cue (played on a read), and a break cue (played when the clock is destroyed). Pick none for a silent clock.

Destroyable (checkbox). When checked, the clock can be smashed by bombs and projectiles; when unchecked, it's permanent.

A calendar is the same object built for the current date instead of the time; see the calendars topic.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the clock sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the press clip of the highlighted theme and hold control and press L to hear its ticking loop.

Authoring clocks by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a single clock is: clock x y "text" clocktype destroyable. On 3d maps a z follows y: clock x y z "text" clocktype destroyable. A ranged clock replaces the single tile with minimum and maximum pairs: clock minx maxx miny maxy "text" clocktype destroyable, inserting a minimum and maximum z after the y pair on 3d maps. The text is wrapped in double quotes, destroyable is the literal word true or false, and the clock sound must match a clock sounds folder name or the word none.
